Russia and Turkey: Alliance of the “Incompatible”
It was a gesture that ended in a crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce the formal end of an eight-month-long verbal war and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterpart in the luxurious hall of the palace in St. Petersburg, I had the impression that Ankara wanted more of this reconciliation.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin did not smile and hardly radiated warmth from him, even by his measured standards.
On the contrary, Recep Tayyip Erdogan has repeatedly spoken of his "dear friend" Mr. Putin - five times, as one of the reports states.
I didn't count.
He also promised that relations with Russia would not only return to their pre-crisis level, but would be even better.
The next day, a local newspaper reported that Erdogan was acting as if nothing bad had ever happened.
In my opinion, his enthusiasm revealed the exact opposite.
But the persistent cold that was radiating from Putin showed that the Russian leader had forgotten nothing.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: the downing of a Russian warplane by Turkey on the Syrian border.
Moscow’s reaction was furious.
Putin was handing out wounds around him and accused Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The scandal was all the greater because it came from an alleged friend.
Rebuilding true trust will be difficult, perhaps even impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
The state-controlled media has waged a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara for months.
All of a sudden, the Turks seemed to be responsible for everything.
More serious were accusations from top officials that Erdogan’s own family benefited from the illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He vehemently denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message came that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting took place only because Putin received the apology he asked from President Erdogan.
Russia could have declared some kind of victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of a ceasefire are clear.
First of all, Erdogan was almost stripped of power during the failed coup last month and therefore needs all of his friends.
The repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have also visibly shaken him.
There is also an economic motive.
Russia’s sanctions have had a severe impact – in particular, the cancellation of charter flights, which transport several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year.
This number has decreased by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, tour operators and charter companies will certainly take a break here if flights are resumed.
They make money on Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruits and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey would be allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," the Vedemosti newspaper reported.
However, the visit had further political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry at the West for what it sees as a poor response to the coup attempt.
In addition, the long-standing hostility of lengthy talks about EU membership and Putin’s accession – which he longs to be able to take advantage of the cooling and break Turkey’s ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly earned bonus points when Ankara asked him to help the elected authorities after the attempted coup.
You must understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-rooted fear of regime change, this is given.
So the summit in this pompous, seaside palace of Russia and Turkey allowed me to demonstrate what one analyst described to me as an “alliance of incompatibles”: how the forces of two countries that feel rejected and exploited by the West unite.
