Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You're from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, not far from the Spanish border.
I've moved quite a lot.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
I studied journalism in France, and then I got to work in a magazine.
Why did you decide to move out of the country?
I started to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere between people.
I think every Frenchman is very negative.
People in France are negative in general, but it has gotten worse recently.
It’s interesting that you’re talking about negativity.
This is how some people view the Czech character.
Believe me, you're not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not feel this way when they come to France, because they don’t see it as much as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
A big topic is money.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which I think is enough.
Now there is a problem with the behavior of people towards Muslims.
This is completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, on the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor started looking at me through his fingers just because I was Muslim.
It's like I'm some kind of evil.
That's why I didn't feel good in France.
But my family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job basically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy at Air France here in Prague.
I admit that I did not know Prague at all from the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I did not know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here three years now, and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Especially because of a completely different atmosphere.
Maybe it’s because I don’t speak Czech, so I can’t capture any negative reactions or insults, but I feel that there are more free people here.
That I could do anything, dress any way, and no one would judge me.
In France, someone always looks at you unpleasantly, for example, when you have special clothes and the like.
I started to feel really free in Prague.
I don't think people care about that kind of thing.
Where do you work now?
After working for Air France, I worked for a travel website.
Then one of my friends and I started a website where people offer and look for shared housing.
We are currently operating only in Prague, but we would like to extend it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends who are half Czechs and two other friends of Czech.
I must say that another specificity of the Czechs is that at first they keep more distance.
They won't let anyone near their body right away.
This is quite different from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses on their faces.
It's different here, but I understand it's a cultural thing, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned that you don't speak Czech.
Is language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, it is quite simple in Prague, because everyone here speaks English.
Even in the evenings or in the food.
I would like to learn Czech, but I don’t have that much time.
And since everyone can communicate in English at least a little, I don’t have such a need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone to help me.
Have you experienced any negative reactions?
Maybe because you are a Muslim?
No, not really.
Perhaps it is also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My leader, the Czech Republic, once told me about the French football team and said something in the sense: They are not French, they are Africans.
That touched me quite a bit.
But that someone had a problem with being a Muslim hasn't happened to me yet.
Even though a colleague once warned me about some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go to the mall, that they would curse me there.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly linked to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something like Paris, Nice or Brussels could happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is, anything can happen anywhere these days.
Until recently, I could not have imagined that something like this would happen in France.
This is not just about Muslims.
Islam does not recognize violence.
For me, the people who kill are not Muslims.
The Koran says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel about terrorists defending their faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even though I shouldn't feel that way at all.
I try not to follow the reports of violence very much, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that is not really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for the terrorists?
We met at the Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>ho z Pod<0xC4><0x9B>brady Square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians protested against the violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know that.
But I understand that these people feel the need to prove that they don't agree with violence.
I don't think they have to do anything like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn't cause?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
My colleagues, for example, are from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They are a little more religious than I am, so we sometimes have quite wild discussions about Islam because we all perceive it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, maybe they studied Islam in school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate status of women.
How do you see it?
I don't feel inferior in any way.
On the contrary.
I'm a woman, I have strength.
This also means that you don’t wear a head covering.
A hijab, for example?
And it's mostly about the way I was raised.
My mother, for example, is a true Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but he doesn’t wear a scarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It all depends on how you interpret it.
When a person reads the Quran, he should make his own opinion on these things.
So when I read a passage in the Qur’an that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I thought, “I am not the Prophet’s wife, so why should I hide?”
On the other hand, I respect that, and when I come to Iran or Saudi Arabia, for example, where scarves are required, I take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
I haven't felt so good anywhere else.
I have been thinking about Poland for a while, but I feel great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
Prague is the ideal city for this.
