"Protesting Generations" in Ethiopia, a longtime U.S. ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say many protesters were shot dead during clashes with police.
Is there a threat of war in Ethiopia?
In the past decade, it has been one of the most stable nations in Africa, a solid Western alliance with a fast-growing economy.
But in recent months, the country has been gripped by anti-government riots, which are spreading to more and more areas.
In the last week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
According to human rights groups, the government’s response was merciless.
Witnesses say police officers shot and killed crowds of unarmed demonstrators.
Video clips of the protests, probably from the end of last year or the beginning of this year, show members of the security forces beating young people with sticks after being forced to stand by the wall on their hands.
The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country together and it will be even more difficult to move forward,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project for the International Crisis Group research group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous nation in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is backed by the West.
The U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to eliminate the threat of a terrorist attack in the region, particularly in Somalia, and few, if any, African countries receive such assistance from the West.
Ethiopia’s economy was developing at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new suburban train running in the capital city of Addis Ababa.
And the streets of the city are typically quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia can hardly be described as a model of democracy - human rights organizations are constantly talking about government repression - the opposition in the country has been suppressed, dissidents effectively silenced.
Many were exiled, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the desert.
However, that can change.
“When you strangle people and they have no choice but to protest, there will be a breakthrough,” said Seyoum Teshome, who lectures at the University of Central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
An entire generation has protested.
There are many complaints, ranging from land disputes to absolute control over the power of the ruling coalition.
After last year’s election, which was widely criticized, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat held by the opposition and now controls 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, the pressure on the border with Eritrea is increasing, and the conflict along this imprecisely marked, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Anylitists fear that separatist groups that have been more or less suppressed in recent years, such as the Oromian Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the confusion and re-arm themselves.
There are several factors that explain why now, after years of smoking under the surface, these bitter feelings have rekindled.
The first one is seemingly harmless: smart phones.
Many Ethiopians can communicate via social networks until the last few years, when cheaper smartphones have become commonly available and the provision of Internet services has improved.
And even if the government bans access to Facebook or Twitter, as is usually the case especially during protests, many people can still communicate via internet proxy, which will hide the location of these people.
Several young Ethiopians spoke about how they had gathered for the protests.
There is also greater solidarity between the Oroms and the Amhars, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oromians and the Amhars are not natural allies.
For centuries, the Amhars, mostly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, have excelled in politics and commerce and exploited the Oroms, many of whom are Muslims and live in the lowlands.
But that's changing, too.
"We are on our way to unified leadership," Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of the Oroms, said.
The largest protests took place in the areas inhabited by Amhara and Oroma.
Many Amhars and Oroms believe that Ethiopia is wrongly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which accounts for about 6 percent of the population and controls the military, intelligence, trade, and politics.
The third cause of the riots is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Zenawi, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia’s prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012, when he succumbed to an unspecified illness.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around the corner.
Analysts say he was particularly masterful at detecting initial signals of dissatisfaction and using envoys to process opponents and win over to his side.
“The current regime lacks basic knowledge,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalegn, was pulled out of relative obscurity in order to replace Zenawi.
Unlike Zenawi, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say they have no confidence in security services controlled by the Tigres.
Many fear that the result will be more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such riots was in 2005, when thousands of people protested against what analysts described as elections that the government plundered and then stole.
A hard-hit followed, during which many protesters were killed - albeit less than in recent months - and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia’s leaders for their visionary infrastructure planning, such as a new suburban train and measurable progress in the fight against poverty.
It is clear, however, that the gradual escalation of disputes within the Ethiopian government has not stopped this.
And there is a dangerous ethnic formation.
Protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked Tigrean-owned businesses last month, and resentment against Tigreans on social media is becoming more common.
Analysts say the protests put the U.S. and other Western allies in an uncomfortable situation.
The U.S. government is using Ethiopia as a base for drone flights over neighboring Somalia, although it has recently declared that the base has been closed.
While the West wants to unequivocally support democracy, at the same time it does not want its ally to disintegrate in an already volatile region.
"That," said Abdi, "is a very sharp edge of the blade."
