Equally feared was the new budget diet: Mysterious foods, such as meatballs and casseroles, have spread as “an amazing way to take advantage of the leftovers,” Zieglerman noted, as chefs could hide unaesthetic ingredients under a layer of cream sauce.
Fresh fruit was replaced with cheaper dried fruit.
Meat - for many years the focal point of American food - has become an economically allocated luxury.
The strange mixtures, which were supposed to serve as a calorie and nutritious filler, took precedence over taste or even common sense when cooking.
During research for a book containing recipes, Ms. Siegelman prepared a period dish of roasted onion stuffed with peanut butter.
