"In a simulation of the GISS model, Venus, during a slow rotation, exposes its daily side to the sun for almost two months at a time," said GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a new report.
This heats up the surface and creates rain, creating a dense layer of clouds that behave like an umbrella and protect the surface from too much solar heat.
The result is a climate with average temperatures that are actually slightly lower than they are currently on Earth.
The model compiled the story of Venus similar to the evolution previously hypothetically compiled by planetary scientists.
Although Venus was probably habitable in the past -- over a few billion years -- it was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation.
Its oceans evaporated and water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light.
Hydrogen has escaped, and only the dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly effects of greenhouse gas remains -- that's Venus as we know it today.
The researchers published their results from the new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
