Kepler measures the speed of rotation of stars in the Pleiades
The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope to help astronomers is to obtain an almost complete list of the rotational speeds of stars from the Pleiades cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, and also how the rotation time is related to the formation of the planet.
“We hope that by comparing our results with other clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between stellar matter, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech’s Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena.
The Pleiades cluster is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now reaching adulthood and have formed over 125 million years.
Now it spins the fastest.
At peak rotational speeds, these teenage stars release huge amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of stars, they have a slowing effect on them.
As the star ages, its rotation speed slows down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by measuring the time between the detection of recognizable points on stars -- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational speeds, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, bigger ones make pirouettes slower than smaller ones.
"In the Pleiades ballet, we see that the slower-spinning stars are more massive, while the fastest-spinning stars are usually very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing star quality and rotational speeds.
“The Pleiades provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in younger and older stars,” Rebull said.
There’s still a lot to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down their rotational speed, so to speak, “hanging their dance shoes on a nail.”
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of the Pleiades’ rotation speed in three studies, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a Qualification Agreement Necessary?
If I did not register, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could move to another hospital?
Is it possible to work after graduation without enrolling in specialized education?
My point is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a somewhat distant hospital, but in about half a year there could be a place in another, where I would like to work.
I do not know how to deal with the situation in the last six months, the question continues.
Responds Mgr. Lenka Vlkov<0xC3><0xA1>.
No legislation provides for the obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with an employer - a hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institute governed by the Labour Code and may be concluded between an employee and an employer in order to ensure the reimbursement of the costs incurred in increasing or deepening the employee’s qualifications.
In the health sector, however, there is a long-term pressure not to conclude these agreements with a view to ensuring the labour mobility of health workers, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
Pursuant to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognizing professional competence and specialised competence to practice the medical profession of a doctor, dentist and pharmacist, it is expressly true that participation in specialised training is considered to be an extension of qualification (not an increase in it).
This means that a qualification agreement can be concluded according to the Labour Code only if the costs reach at least CZK 75,000.
There is no legal requirement or obligation to enrol in specialised education.
The law only determines the conditions for the application for inclusion in the field of specialized education.
However, according to the law, a doctor is entitled to practice the profession of a doctor already thanks to the completion of the necessary university studies, although under the conditions laid down by the law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law provides for a situation in which professional practice completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialist education of a doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
Theoretically, it would be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the situation of the interviewer.
However, given that I do not know the specific circumstances of this case, it is advisable to consult the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (the Department of Science and Medical Professions), since the Ministry of Health by law provides advisory and consultancy services related to the inclusion in specialised education and its course.
The advisory service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
